member.remarks:
Requires two delegates: a search delegate that returns matching options for a query string, and a lookup delegate that resolves a single value back to its display option.
Options are created using with the parameter order (label, value): the label is displayed to the user, and the value is stored when selected.
var country = UseState<string?>(default(string));
QueryResult<Option<string>[]> SearchCountries(IViewContext ctx, string query) => ctx.UseQuery<Option<string>[], (string, string)>( key: ("countries", query), fetcher: ct => Task.FromResult(countries .Where(c => c.Name.Contains(query, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase)) .Select(c => new Option<string>(c.Name, c.Code)) // label: Name, value: Code .ToArray()));
country.ToAsyncSelectInput(SearchCountries, LookupCountry, "Search countries...");

The parameter order is (label, value) — the label is what the user sees in the dropdown,
and the value is what gets stored/returned when the option is selected.


// label: "Germany", value: "DE"
new Option<string>("Germany", "DE")

// label: "John Doe", value: userId (Guid)
new Option<Guid>("John Doe", userId, group: "Engineering")
